05686nam a22006375i 9780292761537DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211964txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927615377 a10.7560/7343642doi  a(DE-B1597)588532  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPN2248 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a792.209731 aHodge, Francis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aYankee Theatre :bThe Image of America on the Stage, 1825–1850 /cFrancis Hodge. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1964  a1 online resource (332 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tPrologue -- tPart I. The Background -- t1. The English Traveler's View of American Life and Theatre -- t2. America's Self-Examination: A Changing Culture, the Stage, and a New Audience -- t3. The Yankee as a Symbol of American Life -- t4. Actor Inspiration: Charles Mathews and Satire on America -- tPart II. Borrowing and Innovation -- t5. James H. Hackett: The First Native Yankee in London -- t6. Hackett Learns the Trade, 1828-1832 -- t7. Hackett's Second London Tour, 1832-1833 -- t8. Hackett Expands the Repertoire -- tPart 3. Flowering and Climax -- t9. Yankee Hill: From Storyteller to Stock Actor to Star -- t10. Hill's Search for Individuality: Building the Repertoire -- t11. Yankee Hill in London -- t12. After London: Hill's Success and Decline -- tPart 4. Change and Decline -- t13. Dan Marble and the Western Hybrid -- t14. Joshua Silsbee: A "Go-Ahead" American -- tEpilogue -- tAppendixes -- tBibliography And Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe famous "Stage Yankees," with their eccentric New England dialect comedy, entertained audiences from Boston to New Orleans, from New York to London in the years between 1825 and 1850. They provided the creative energy for the development of an American-type character in early plays of native authorship. This book examines the full range of their theatre activity, not only as actors, but also as playmakers, and re-evaluates their contribution to the growth of the American stage. Yankee theatre was not an oddity, a passing fad, or an accident of entertainment; it was an honest exploitation of the materials of American life for an audience in search of its own identification. The delineation of the American character—a full-length realistic portrait in the context of stage comedy—was its projected goal; and though not the only method for such delineation, the theatre form was the most popular and extensive way of disseminating the American image. The Yankee actors openly borrowed from what literary sources were available to them, but because of their special position as actors, who were required to give flesh-and-blood imitations of people for the believable acceptance of others viewing the same people about them, they were forced to draw extensively on their actors' imaginations and to present the American as they saw him. If the image was too often an external one, it still revealed the Yankee as a hardy individual whose independence was a primary assumption; as a bargainer, whose techniques were more clever than England's sharpest penny-pincher; as a country person, more intelligent, sharper and keener in dealings than the city-bred type; as an American freewheeler who always landed on top, not out of naive honesty but out of a simple perception of other human beings and their gullibility. Much new evidence in this study is based on London productions, where the view of English audiences and critics was sharply focused on what Americans thought about themselves and the new culture of democracy emerging around them. The shift from America, the borrower, to America, the original doer, can be clearly seen in this stager activity. Yankee theatre, then, is an epitome of the emerging American after the Second War for Independence. Emerging nationalism meant emerging national definition. Yankee theatre thus led to the first cohesive body of American plays, the first American actors seen in London, and to a new realistic interpretation of the American in the "character" plays of the 1870s and 1880s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAmerican drama (Comedy)xHistory and criticism. 0aComedianszUnited States. 0aTheaterzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/73436440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292761537423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292761537/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK